# Review-pipeline grounding scan (review-reusable.yml semgrep step).
# Frozen at 1.111.0 so AI reviewer signal stays comparable across runs;
# bumping disrupts grounding fingerprints. Dependabot is configured to
# ignore all semgrep bumps (major / minor / patch) for this lock only —
# even 1.111.x → 1.111.y patch bumps shift the AI reviewer's grounding
# fingerprint, so policy is "all bumps are manual" (see dependabot.yml).
#
# Regenerate the locked requirements.txt on Python 3.11 (matches the
# `actions/setup-python` version pinned in review-reusable.yml). 3.11 is the
# newest interpreter semgrep 1.111.0 declares in its classifiers; its
# Requires-Python (>=3.9) has no upper bound, so a newer Python installs fine
# and then dies at import time.
# Run it from INSIDE this directory:
#   cd .github-deps/semgrep-review
#   python3.11 -m venv .tmp/pip-compile-venv
#   .tmp/pip-compile-venv/bin/pip install pip-tools
#   .tmp/pip-compile-venv/bin/pip-compile \
#     --generate-hashes --no-emit-index-url --strip-extras --allow-unsafe \
#     --output-file=requirements.txt requirements.in
# --allow-unsafe is required HERE and only here: it is what admits the pinned
# `setuptools` below into the lock at all. Dependabot's write path omits the
# flag, but it never writes this lock — every bump in it is ignored (see
# dependabot.yml) — so the asymmetry is inert. This directory is deliberately
# not under `.github/`; see the validate lock's requirements.in (#191).
semgrep==1.111.0

# semgrep pulls opentelemetry-instrumentation, which imports `pkg_resources`.
# setuptools removed pkg_resources in 81.0, so an unconstrained resolve pins a
# setuptools that makes semgrep fail to start. This is not a style preference:
# it is the difference between the Stage 0 detector running and reporting zero
# findings because it never ran.
setuptools<81
